# Supabase Guidelines

## Clients
- Use `@supabase/ssr` package (NOT `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs` — deprecated)
- Three factories live in `lib/supabase/`:
  - `server.ts` — for Server Components, Server Actions, Route Handlers (reads cookies)
  - `client.ts` — for Client Components (browser)
  - `admin.ts` — service role, SERVER-ONLY, never expose

## Auth
- Email/password via `supabase.auth.signInWithPassword`
- Proxy (`proxy.ts` at the project root — renamed from `middleware.ts` in Next 16) refreshes the session on every request via `lib/supabase/proxy.ts`
- Layouts (not pages) enforce auth — redirect in `(member)/layout.tsx` and `admin/layout.tsx`
- Check role in the layout via a DB query to `profiles` (use `lib/auth.ts` `getCurrentProfile()`); never trust JWT metadata for authZ
- For role gates that should 403 (not redirect), call `forbidden()` from `next/navigation` — requires `experimental.authInterrupts: true` in `next.config.ts` (already enabled)

## RLS — mandatory rules
1. Every new table: `alter table X enable row level security;` in the same migration
2. Write explicit policies for SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE — no catch-all
3. Always scope by `org_id` for multi-tenant tables
4. Test policies: write a SQL test that tries to access another org's data as a member, expect empty result

## Migrations
- One migration file per logical change, named `YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_description.sql`
- Always include both forward migration and the corresponding RLS policies
- Never edit an already-applied migration — write a new one

## Generated types
- After any schema change: `npx supabase gen types typescript --local > types/database.ts`
- Use `Database['public']['Tables']['menus']['Row']` style imports, not hand-written types

## Common mistakes to avoid
- Don't use `supabase.auth.getSession()` in server code — use `getUser()` (it revalidates)
- Don't forget `await` on `cookies()` in Next.js 15+
- Don't query with service role from user-facing code — bypasses RLS and is a critical security hole
